</i> ‘meadow’. Compare   Thwaites  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Thwaites","meanings":["English: from the northern English placename <i>Thwaite</i> (Old Norse <i>thveit</i> ‘meadow, paddock’) + plural or post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>. The plural form is found in several placenames, including Thwaites in Keighley (Yorkshire), which is a principal source of the surname."]},{"name":"Tweed","meanings":["Irish (Antrim; of Norman origin): variant of   Tuite  .","English (mainly East Anglia): sometimes a variant of   Thwaites  , or   Twite  .","Scottish: probably a shortened form of   Tweddle  ."]},{"name":"Tuitt","meanings":["Irish (of Norman origin): variant of   Tuite  ."]}]},{"name":"Richard","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Rikert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]},{"name":"Rickert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Lady Richard de Tuite was born in 1178, in County Westmeath, Ireland. She had at least 2 sons with Sir Richard de Tuite."},"et":{"1178–":"1178–Surnud","1172–1211":"1172–1211","1199–1269":"1199–1269","1201–1282":"1201–1282","1178–Female":"1178–Surnud","1269":"1269","1201":"1201","1178":"1178","1211":"1211","1199":"1199","ABT 1201":"umbes 1201","1282":"1282","1172":"1172","County Westmeath, Ireland":"County Westmeath, Iirimaa","Marston, Westmeath, Ireland":"Marston, County Waterford, Iirimaa"},"fi":{"1178–":"1178–Kuollut","1172–1211":"1172–1211","1199–1269":"1199–1269","1201–1282":"1201–1282","1178–Female":"1178–Kuollut","1269":"1269","1201":"1201","1178":"1178","1211":"1211","1199":"1199","ABT 1201":"noin 1201","1282":"1282","1172":"1172","County Westmeath, Ireland":"County Westmeath, Irlanti","Marston, Westmeath, Ireland":"Marston, County Waterford, Irlanti"},"fr":{"1178–":"1178–Décédée","1172–1211":"1172–1211","1199–1269":"1199–1269","1201–1282":"1201–1282","1178–Female":"1178–Décédée","1269":"1269","1201":"1201","1178":"1178","1211":"1211","1199":"1199","ABT 1201":"environ 1201","1282":"1282","1172":"1172","County Westmeath, Ireland":"County Westmeath, Irlande","Marston, Westmeath, Ireland":"Marston, County Waterford, Irlande","lifeSummary":"Lady Richard de Tuite est née en 1178, à County Westmeath, Irlande. Elle a eu au moins 2 fils avec Sir Richard de Tuite."},"de":{"1178–":"1178–Verstorben","1172–1211":"1172–1211","1199–1269":"1199–1269","1201–1282":"1201–1282","1178–Female":"1178–Verstorben","1269":"1269","1201":"1201","1178":"1178","1211":"1211","1199":"1199","ABT 1201":"um 1201","1282":"1282","1172":"1172","County Westmeath, Ireland":"County Westmeath, Irland","Marston, Westmeath, Ireland":"Marston, County Waterford, Irland"